be brought to justice without delay,\u201d Aliyev said in a statement issued by the presidency following a Security Council meeting.He demanded an explanation from Iranian authorities, saying Baku expects an official apology and criminal accountability for those responsible.Aliyev also argued that the incident was not the first such \u201cterrorist act\u201d against Azerbaijan, recalling the attack on the Azerbaijani embassy in Tehran in January 2023, which he said had been ordered at the highest levels of Iran\u2019s state institutions.\u201cThis time, our response will be the same. We will not tolerate this unprovoked act of terror and aggression against Azerbaijan,\u201d he said.Aliyev added that Azerbaijan\u2019s armed forces had been ordered to prepare appropriate retaliatory measures while emphasizing that his country does not allow its territory to be used against neighboring states.\u201cAzerbaijan has not and will not participate in operations against Iran,\u201d he said, describing it as a principled position.Earlier Thursday, Azerbaijan\u2019s Foreign Ministry said drones launched from Iran struck Nakhchivan, with one hitting the terminal building of Nakhchivan International Airport and another falling near a school in the village of Shakarabad.\u201cWe strongly condemn these drone attacks launched from the territory of the Islamic Republic of Iran,\u201d the ministry said, noting that the strike caused damage to the airport building and injuries to civilians.The Health Ministry later said four people were injured, while the Defense Ministry reported that four drones were launched in the attack.Iran denied responsibility for the incident. During a phone call with Azerbaijani Foreign Minister Jeyhun Bayramov, Iranian Foreign Minister Abbas Araghchi said no projectiles had been launched toward Azerbaijan and that Iranian forces were investigating the matter.", "content": "ONLY AVAILABLE IN PAID PLANS", "keywords": ["world"], "creator": ["agencies"], "langua